### EXAMPLE 5: UNCHECKED_LOW_LEVEL_CALLS VULNERABILITY

**Vulnerable Code:**
```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.4.0;

contract demo{

    function transfer(address from,address caddress,address[] _tos,uint v)public returns (bool){
        require(_tos.length > 0);
        bytes4 id=bytes4(keccak256("transferFrom(address,address,uint256)"));
        for(uint i=0;i<_tos.length;i++){
            caddress.call(id,from,_tos[i],v);
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

**Security Analysis:**
This code contains a unchecked_low_level_calls vulnerability.

Here’s a concise, refined write-up of the issue:

1. What the code does  
   • Public function `transfer(from, caddress, _tos, v)` loops over each address in `_tos`.  
   • For each recipient it issues a low-level call:  
     `caddress.call(keccak256("transferFrom(address,address,uint256)"), from, _tos[i], v);`  
   • It never checks whether that call succeeded or not, and in the end it always returns `true`.  

2. Why it’s vulnerable  
   • Unchecked low-level calls  
     – By calling `caddress.call(...)` directly and ignoring the Boolean return, any failure inside the token’s `transferFrom` (whether it reverts or returns `false`) is silently ignored. The wrapper will still return `true` as if the transfer succeeded.  
   • Denial-of-service via gas griefing  
     – Because `.call` forwards all remaining gas, a malicious or buggy token contract at `caddress` can (in its `transferFrom` or fallback) loop indefinitely, revert, or burn gas—causing your entire transaction to run out of gas or revert before completing the loop.  

3. Exploit conditions  
   • The caller is free to specify any contract as `caddress`. If that contract implements a malicious `transferFrom` (or even just a fallback that reverts or consumes lots of gas), it can:  
     – Prevent any of the intended token transfers from ever succeeding.  
     – Waste caller’s gas and revert the whole multi-transfer call.  
   • Because you never check the result, callers will believe they “succeeded” even when no tokens moved.  

4. Impact & severity  
   • Tokens may never actually be transferred despite the wrapper returning success.  
   • Funds/calls can be DoS’d or wasted.  

5. Mitigation recommendations  
   • Don’t use low-level `.call` for ERC-20 operations. Instead:  
     ```
     require(ERC20(caddress).transferFrom(from, _tos[i], v), "Transfer failed");
     ```  
   • Or use OpenZeppelin’s SafeERC20 which wraps calls and checks return values.  
   • If you must use `.call`, always check the returned `bool success` and optionally the returned data.


**Classification**: This code contains a **unchecked_low_level_calls** vulnerability.

